<font color="#FF0000">LOOK AT VIETNAM'S CULTURE</font><br>
<tt>Thu Nov 20  2:26:43 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Respect for elders is deeply intrenched in the culture of Eastern societies, communist or non-communist.  I think we tend to forget that the &quot;communists&quot; are a relatively recent part of the entire culture, which is connected to the Buddhist religion and has been around a few thousand years.  When we realize that &quot;communism&quot; in the Vietnamese culture is less than 60 years old, maybe we can appreciate that there is a deeply ingrained structural support for veterans of war.  This phenomina may not be hard to understand in this light.  <br><br>
When we look at ourselves, we see a &quot;compartmentalized&quot; society, where we have to have formal means of interacting.  I think a look at Vietnamese society would show that things are much less &quot;compartmentalized&quot; or &quot;institutionalized.&quot; <br><br>
What I am saying is that it is very possible that the story above is fairly accurate.
